{"title_page": "ISO/IEC 27005", "text_new": "{{copy edit|date=April 2020|for=haphazard grammar, doubtful phrasing, lazy bullet-pointing, and highly inventive spelling}}\n\n\n\nISO/IEC stands for International Organization for Standardization/International Electrotechnical Commission. '''ISO/IEC 27005''' provides guidelines and techniques for information security risk management to support the concepts in [[ISO/IEC 27001]] standards. '''ISO/IEC 27005''' is designed to assist the implementation of information security based on a risk management approach<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iso.org/standard/75281.html|title=BS EN ISO/IEC 27005:2018 \u2013 What is ISO/IEC 27005?|website=www.iso.org|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>.\n\n'''ISO/IEC 27005''' is part of a big family of standards in the information security management system (ISMS), and therefore, it appears in [[ISO/IEC 27000-series]] (find more information in [[ISO/IEC 27000]]). \n\nWithin the [[ISO/IEC 27000-series|ISO/IEC 27000]] family of standards, it is listed as '''\u00a0ISO/IEC 27005''' Information technology \u2014 Security techniques \u2014 Information security risk management. ISO/IEC 27001 and ISO/IEC 27002 standards serve as the cornerstone to understand and appreciate ISO/IEC 27005 standard fully.\n== What does the standard establishes? ==\nISO/IEC 27005 is a standard that does not specify or recommend any risk management method. It implicates or includes a continual process that consists of a structured sequence of activities and some of the iteratives:<ref>{{cite web|title=BS EN ISO/IEC 27005:2018 \u2013 Content of the standard |url=https://www.iso27001security.com/html/27005.html|website=www.iso27001security.com|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n* Establish a risk management context.\n* Assess relevant information quantitatively or qualitatively.\n* Treat the risks appropriately.\n* Keep stakeholders informed throughout the process.\n* Monitor and review risks, risk treatments, obligations, and criteria; and respond to significant changes appropriately.\n\n== Objectives ==\nThis standard is mainly oriented to companies, although it is useful for any type of organization that wants to improve its Information Security Management System (ISMS) or that may suffer certain security problems in its company, for which it is not necessary to apply the entire methodology of the standard, just focus on a number of factors, such as the actual scope of the Information Security Management System (ISMS), or the commercial sector of the industry itself.\n\nTherefore, its main objective is to improve information security risk management in an organization, implying the specific methodology for each information security problem, that is, a specific methodology that will not be used for all Information Security Management System.\n\n== Terms and structure ==\nThe following sections are part of the ISO/IEC 27005 standard:<ref>{{cite web|title=BS EN ISO/IEC 27005:2018 \u2013 Sections of ISO/IEC 27005|url=https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:std:iso-iec:27005:ed-3:v1:en|website=www.iso.org|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n* Foreword.\n* Introduction.\n* Scope.\n* Normative References.\n* Terms and definitions.\n* Structure of this document.\n* Background.\n* Description of the process of ISRM.\n* Context establishment.\n* Information on Security Risk Assessment.\n* Treatment of Information Security Risks.\n* Risk Admission Information security.\n* Communication of information security risks.\n* Safety Information Risk Tracking and Review.\n* Annexes\n** Annex A: Definition of the scope of the process.\n** Annex B: Asset valuation and impact evaluation.\n** Annex C: Examples of typical threats.\n** Annex D: Vulnerabilities and vulnerability assessment methods.\n*** Annex E: Information Security Risk Management approaches.\n\nIt is important to note that these annexes can inform about impacts; vulnerabilities and threats can support in facing risks of the same type with information assets under evaluation.\n\n== Benefits of certificate: ==\nPersonal Evaluation and Certification Board (PECB) is an organization that provides ISO training. A certificate in ISO/IEC 27005 Certificate can be obtained to gain certain benefits:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pecb.com/en|title=BS EN ISO/IEC 27005:2018 \u2013 Benefits of Certification|website=pecb.com|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n* The skills gained from this certification can be used to support the effective implementation of an information security risk management process in an organization.\n* The acquired expertise can be used to responsibly manage an information security risk management process and ensure conformity with legal and regulatory requirements.\n* It can provide an ability to manage an information security and risk management team.\n* It can also provide the ability to support an organization to align its ISMS objectives.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External Links ==\n\n* [http://www.iso.org/iso/en/CatalogueDetailPage.CatalogueDetail?CSNUMBER=42505&ICS1=35&ICS2=40&ICS3= ISO Website]\n\n{{ISO standards}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:ISO IEC 27005}}\n\n\n[[Category:Information assurance standards]]\n[[Category:ISO/IEC 27000-series|#27005]]\n", "text_old": "{{copy edit|date=April 2020|for=haphazard grammar, doubtful phrasing, lazy bullet-pointing, and highly inventive spelling}}\n\n\n\nISO/IEC stands for International Organization for Standardization/International Electrotechnical Commission. '''ISO/IEC 27005''' provides guidelines and techniques for information security risk management to support the concepts in [[ISO/IEC 27001]] standards. '''ISO/IEC 27005''' is designed to assist the implementation of information security based on a risk management approach<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iso.org/standard/75281.html|title=BS EN ISO/IEC 27005:2018 \u2013 What is ISO/IEC 27005?|website=www.iso.org|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>.\n\n'''ISO/IEC 27005''' is part of a big family of standards in the information security management system (ISMS), and therefore, it appears in [[ISO/IEC 27000-series]] (find more information in [[ISO/IEC 27000]]). \n\nWithin the [[ISO/IEC 27000-series|ISO/IEC 27000]] family of standards, it is listed as '''\u00a0ISO/IEC 27005''' Information technology \u2014 Security techniques \u2014 Information security risk management. ISO/IEC 27001 and ISO/IEC 27002 standards serve as the cornerstone to understand and appreciate ISO/IEC 27005 standard fully.\n== What does the standard establishes? ==\nISO/IEC 27005 is a standard that does not specify or recommend any risk management method. It implicates or includes a continual process that consists of a structured sequence of activities and some of the iteratives:<ref>{{cite web|title=BS EN ISO/IEC 27005:2018 \u2013 Content of the standard |url=https://www.iso27001security.com/html/27005.html|website=www.iso27001security.com|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n* Establish a risk management context.\n* Assess relevant information quantitatively or qualitatively.\n* Treat the risks appropriately.\n* Keep stakeholders informed throughout the process.\n* Monitor and review risks, risk treatments, obligations, and criteria; and respond to significant changes appropriately.\n\n== Objectives ==\nThis standard is mainly oriented to companies, although it is useful for any type of organization that wants to improve its Information Security Management System (ISMS) or that may suffer certain security problems in its company, for which it is not necessary to apply the entire methodology of the standard, just focus on a number of factors, such as the actual scope of the Information Security Management System (ISMS), or the commercial sector of the industry itself.\n\nTherefore, its main objective is to improve information security risk management in an organization, implying the specific methodology for each information security problem, that is, a specific methodology that will not be used for all Information Security Management System.\n\n== Terms and structure ==\nThe following sections are part of the ISO/IEC 27005 standard:<ref>{{cite web|title=BS EN ISO/IEC 27005:2018 \u2013 Sections of ISO/IEC 27005|url=https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:std:iso-iec:27005:ed-3:v1:en|website=www.iso.org|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n* Foreword.\n* Introduction.\n* Scope.\n* Normative References.\n* Terms and definitions.\n* Structure of this document.\n* Background.\n* Description of the process of ISRM.\n* Context establishment.\n* Information on Security Risk Assessment.\n* Treatment of Information Security Risks.\n* Risk Admission Information security.\n* Communication of information security risks.\n* Safety Information Risk Tracking and Review.\n* Annexes\n** Annex A: Definition of the scope of the process.\n** Annex B: Asset valuation and impact evaluation.\n** Annex C: Examples of typical threats.\n** Annex D: Vulnerabilities and vulnerability assessment methods.\n*** Annex E: Information Security Risk Management approaches.\n\nIt is important to note that these annexes can inform about impacts; vulnerabilities and threats can support in facing risks of the same type with information assets under evaluation.\n\n== Benefits of certificate: ==\n\n* Personal Evaluation and Certification Board (PECB) is an organization that provides ISO training. A certificate in ISO/IEC 27005 Certificate can be obtained to gain certain benefits:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pecb.com/en|title=BS EN ISO/IEC 27005:2018 \u2013 Benefits of Certification|website=pecb.com|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n* The skills gained from this certification can be used to support the effective implementation of an information security risk management process in an organization.\n* The acquired expertise can be used to responsibly manage an information security risk management process and ensure conformity with legal and regulatory requirements.\n* It can provide an ability to manage an information security and risk management team.\n* It can also provide the ability to support an organization to align its ISMS objectives.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External Links ==\n\n* [http://www.iso.org/iso/en/CatalogueDetailPage.CatalogueDetail?CSNUMBER=42505&ICS1=35&ICS2=40&ICS3= ISO Website]\n\n{{ISO standards}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:ISO IEC 27005}}\n\n\n[[Category:Information assurance standards]]\n[[Category:ISO/IEC 27000-series|#27005]]\n", "name_user": "Earthianyogi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBenefits of certificate:", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO/IEC_27005"}
{"title_page": "Philip Edward Archer", "text_new": "{{short description|Ghanaian judge}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n'''Philip Edward Archer''' (22 February 1925 - 10 May 2002) was the [[Chief Justice of Ghana]] between 1991 and 1995.<ref name=OSG>Joe Bradford Nyinah, [http://www.modernghana.com/news/9230/1/ex-chief-justice-gets-state-honour.html Ex-Chief Justice gets State Honour], ''[[Daily Graphic (Ghana)|Daily Graphic]]'', 19 May 2000</ref> He was the eighth person to hold this position since Ghana became an independent nation.<ref>\n{{Cite web |url=http://ghana.peacefmonline.com/ghana/government/judiciary/chief_justice/341.php |title=List of Chief Justices |access-date=31 January 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100111203407/http://ghana.peacefmonline.com/ghana/government/judiciary/chief_justice/341.php |archive-date=11 January 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }} \n</ref> He died on 10 May 2002.\n\n==Life==\nPhilip Edward Archer was born 22 February 1925, Abontiakrom, [[Tarkwa]]. He was educated at St Peter's School in [[Sekondi]], [[Adisadel College]], [[Cape Coast]] and the [[University of Nottingham]] in England. Admitted a [[Solicitor]] of the [[Senior Courts of England and Wales|Supreme Court of Jurisdiction]] of England and Wales in 1957, he returned to Ghana and joined the office of the Registrar-General. Appointed Registrar-General in 1959 and Judicial Secretary in 1961, he became a High Court Judge in 1964 and a [[Supreme Court of Ghana|Supreme Court]] Judge in 1980. He was Pro-Chancellor and Chairman of the [[University of Cape Coast]] Council from 1979 to 1983. Retiring as a judge in 1983, he was appointed full-time chairman of the Law Reform Commission. Chief Justice from 1991 until 1995, he was made a Member of the [[Council of State (Ghana)|Council of State]] in 1995. In 2000 he was honoured with the [[Order of the Star of Ghana]].<ref name=OSG/>\nHe died at the [[Korle-Bu Teaching Hospital|Korle Bu Teaching Hospital]] on 10 May 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/artikel.php?ID=25074|title=Justice Archer laid to rest|website=www.ghanaweb.com|language=en|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Supreme Court of Ghana]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box\n|title=[[Supreme Court of Ghana|Chief Justice of Ghana]]\n|before=[[E. N. P. Sowah]]\n|after=[[Isaac Kobina Abban]]\n|years=1991&ndash;1995}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Chief Justices, Ghana}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Archer, Philip Edward}}\n[[Category:1925 births]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian lawyers]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Star of Ghana]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Adisadel College]]\n[[Category:People from Western Region (Ghana)]]\n\n\n{{Ghana-bio-stub}}\n{{Africa-law-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ghanaian judge}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n'''Philip Edward Archer''' (22 February 1925 - 10 May 2002) was the [[Chief Justice of Ghana]] between 1991 and 1995.<ref name=OSG>Joe Bradford Nyinah, [http://www.modernghana.com/news/9230/1/ex-chief-justice-gets-state-honour.html Ex-Chief Justice gets State Honour], ''[[Daily Graphic (Ghana)|Daily Graphic]]'', 19 May 2000</ref> He was the eighth person to hold this position since Ghana became an independent nation.<ref>\n{{Cite web |url=http://ghana.peacefmonline.com/ghana/government/judiciary/chief_justice/341.php |title=List of Chief Justices |access-date=31 January 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100111203407/http://ghana.peacefmonline.com/ghana/government/judiciary/chief_justice/341.php |archive-date=11 January 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }} \n</ref> He died on 10 May 2002.\n\n==Life==\nPhilip Edward Archer was born 22 February 1925, Abontiakrom, [[Tarkwa]]. He was educated at St Peter\u2019s School in [[Sekondi]], [[Adisadel College]], [[Cape Coast]] and the [[University of Nottingham]] in England. Admitted a [[Solicitor]] of the [[Senior Courts of England and Wales|Supreme Court of Jurisdiction]] of England and Wales in 1957, he returned to Ghana and joined the office of the Registrar-General. Appointed Registrar-General in 1959 and Judicial Secretary in 1961, he became a High Court Judge in 1964 and a [[Supreme Court of Ghana|Supreme Court]] Judge in 1980. He was Pro-Chancellor and Chairman of the [[University of Cape Coast]] Council from 1979 to 1983. Retiring as a judge in 1983, he was appointed full-time chairman of the Law Reform Commission. Chief Justice from 1991 until 1995, he was made a Member of the [[Council of State (Ghana)|Council of State]] in 1995. In 2000 he was honoured with the [[Order of the Star of Ghana]].<ref name=OSG/>\nHe died at the [[Korle-Bu Teaching Hospital|Korle Bu Teaching Hospital]] on 10 May 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/artikel.php?ID=25074|title=Justice Archer laid to rest|website=www.ghanaweb.com|language=en|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Supreme Court of Ghana]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box\n|title=[[Supreme Court of Ghana|Chief Justice of Ghana]]\n|before=[[E. N. P. Sowah]]\n|after=[[Isaac Kobina Abban]]\n|years=1991&ndash;1995}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Chief Justices, Ghana}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Archer, Philip Edward}}\n[[Category:1925 births]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian lawyers]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Star of Ghana]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Adisadel College]]\n[[Category:People from Western Region (Ghana)]]\n\n\n{{Ghana-bio-stub}}\n{{Africa-law-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philip_Edward_Archer"}
{"title_page": "Stella Arach-Amoko", "text_new": "{{short description|Ugandan lawyer and judge}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name   =  Stella Arach-Amoko\n| image =\n| image_size  = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = \n| birth_place = [[Uganda]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater  ='''[[Makerere University]]'''<br/> {{small|([[Bachelor of Laws]])}}<br/>'''[[Law Development Centre]]'''<br/>{{small|( [[Legal practice|Diploma in Legal Practice]])}}\n|occupation                 = Lawyer, judge\n| years_active              =  1997 \u2014 present\n| nationality               = Ugandan\n| ethnicity                 = \n| citizenship               = Uganda\n| residence                 = [[Kampala]], Uganda\n| known_for                 = Law\n| networth                  = \n| home_town                 = \n| title                     = Justice of the [[Supreme Court of Uganda]]\n| spouse                    = <small>\n|religion                   = \n}}\n\n'''Stella Arach-Amoko''' is a [[Uganda]]n [[judge]], who has served as a Justice of the [[Supreme Court of Uganda]], since 20 June 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jlos.go.ug/index.php/component/k2/item/314-new-judges-sworn-in |title=New Judges Sworn In | accessdate=14 September 2017 |\ndate=20 June 2013  | publisher=Uganda Justice, Law and Order Sector (JLOS)|  author=JLOS |location=Kampala}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nArach-Amoko served in the Uganda Attorney General's chambers from 1979 until 1997, rising from a state attorney to commissioner for civil litigation. In 1997, she was appointed a High Court judge, serving in that capacity until 2010.<ref name=\"Bio\">{{cite web| author=Isaac Prince Mulindwa  | accessdate=14 September 2017 |url=https://medium.com/@princemulindwaisaac/profiling-the-justices-of-the-supreme-court-the-career-side-b3a3d0e02bc9| title=The Judges of the Supreme Court of Uganda - Their Career Side | publisher=Medium.com|\ndate=21 March 2016 | location=Kampala}}</ref>\n\nJustice Stella Arach-Amoko, served at the [[East African Court of Justice]], from 2006 until 2008, as a judge and from 2008 until 2013, as a \"Deputy Principal Judge of the First Instance Division\". In 2010, she was one of the candidates considered by the Judicial Services Commission, for appointment as the [[Chief Justice of Uganda]].<ref name=\"Bio\"/>\n\nAs of 15 April 2018, Justice Arach-Amoko serves as the Chairperson of  the Management Committee of Uganda's Law Development Centre<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ldc.ac.ug/ldc-management|title=LDC Management {{!}} Law Development Centre|website=www.ldc.ac.ug|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>.\n\n== Personal Life ==\nJustice Arach-Amoko is married to [[Ambassador]] Idule Amoko<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://observer.ug/news/headlines/60492-mabirizi-returns-to-supreme-court-in-new-age-limit-petition|title=Mabirizi returns to Supreme court in new age limit petition|last=BATTE|first=BAKER|website=The Observer - Uganda|language=en-gb|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref> who, as of 2017, was serving as the Deputy Head of Mission at [https://addisababa.mofa.go.ug/data-mmenu-8-Mission-Location.html the Uganda Embassy in Addis Ababa]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://addisababa.mofa.go.ug/data-dnews-50-AMB.-AMUGE-OTENGO-WAS-WARMLY-RECEIVED-BY-THE-UGANDAN-COMMUNITY-IN-ETHIOPIA-AT-A-COLORFUL-EVENT-IN-ADDIS-ABABA-ON-SATURDAY,-18-NOVEMBER-2017.html|title=AMB. AMUGE OTENGO WAS WARMLY RECEIVED BY THE UGANDAN COMMUNITY IN ETHIOPIA AT A COLORFUL EVENT IN ADDIS ABABA ON SATURDAY, 18 NOVEMBER 2017|website=addisababa.mofa.go.ug|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>.\n\nShe also has a [[daughter]] ,Ivy Amoko, who in 2009 was a Gold Winner for Chess in the Inter-University Games with Makerere <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kawowo.com/2014/01/06/ivy-amoko-a-chess-playing-law-clerk/|title=Meet Ivy Amoko, A Chess Playing Law Clerk|last=Isabirye|first=David|date=2014-01-06|website=Kawowo Sports|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>. Ivy Amoko is also a chess Woman FIDE Master<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ratings.fide.com/card.phtml?event=10000291|title=Amoko, Ivy Claire FIDE Chess Profile - Players Arbiters Trainers|website=ratings.fide.com|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Judiciary of Uganda]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.parliament.go.ug/new/index.php/about-parliament/parliamentary-news/214-parliament-vets-appointed-judges Parliament Vets Appointed Judges]\n* [http://allafrica.com/stories/201305131196.html?viewall=1 Who Are the New Judges?]\n\n{{Supreme Court of Uganda}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arach-Amoko, Stella}}\n[[Category:Ugandan judges]]\n[[Category:Ugandan lawyers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ugandan women lawyers]]\n[[Category:Ugandan women judges]]\n[[Category:Makerere University alumni]]\n[[Category:Law Development Centre alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Northern Region, Uganda]]\n[[Category:Justices of the Supreme Court of Uganda]]\n\n\n{{Uganda-law-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ugandan lawyer and judge}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name   =  Stella Arach-Amoko\n| image =\n| image_size  = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = \n| birth_place = [[Uganda]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater  ='''[[Makerere University]]'''<br/> {{small|([[Bachelor of Laws]])}}<br/>'''[[Law Development Centre]]'''<br/>{{small|( [[Legal practice|Diploma in Legal Practice]])}}\n|occupation                 = Lawyer, judge\n| years_active              =  1997 \u2014 present\n| nationality               = Ugandan\n| ethnicity                 = \n| citizenship               = Uganda\n| residence                 = [[Kampala]], Uganda\n| known_for                 = Law\n| networth                  = \n| home_town                 = \n| title                     = Justice of the [[Supreme Court of Uganda]]\n| spouse               