irst=BAKER|website=The Observer - Uganda|language=en-gb|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref> who ,as of 2017 ,was serving as the Deputy Head of Mission at [https://addisababa.mofa.go.ug/data-mmenu-8-Mission-Location.html the Uganda Embassy in Addis Ababa]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://addisababa.mofa.go.ug/data-dnews-50-AMB.-AMUGE-OTENGO-WAS-WARMLY-RECEIVED-BY-THE-UGANDAN-COMMUNITY-IN-ETHIOPIA-AT-A-COLORFUL-EVENT-IN-ADDIS-ABABA-ON-SATURDAY,-18-NOVEMBER-2017.html|title=AMB. AMUGE OTENGO WAS WARMLY RECEIVED BY THE UGANDAN COMMUNITY IN ETHIOPIA AT A COLORFUL EVENT IN ADDIS ABABA ON SATURDAY, 18 NOVEMBER 2017|website=addisababa.mofa.go.ug|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>.\n\nShe also has a [[daughter]] ,Ivy Amoko , who in 2009 was a Gold Winner for Chess in the Inter-University Games with Makerere <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kawowo.com/2014/01/06/ivy-amoko-a-chess-playing-law-clerk/|title=Meet Ivy Amoko, A Chess Playing Law Clerk|last=Isabirye|first=David|date=2014-01-06|website=Kawowo Sports|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>. Ivy Amoko is also a chess Woman FIDE Master<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ratings.fide.com/card.phtml?event=10000291|title=Amoko, Ivy Claire FIDE Chess Profile - Players Arbiters Trainers|website=ratings.fide.com|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Judiciary of Uganda]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.parliament.go.ug/new/index.php/about-parliament/parliamentary-news/214-parliament-vets-appointed-judges Parliament Vets Appointed Judges]\n* [http://allafrica.com/stories/201305131196.html?viewall=1 Who Are the New Judges?]\n\n{{Supreme Court of Uganda}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arach-Amoko, Stella}}\n[[Category:Ugandan judges]]\n[[Category:Ugandan lawyers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ugandan women lawyers]]\n[[Category:Ugandan women judges]]\n[[Category:Makerere University alumni]]\n[[Category:Law Development Centre alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Northern Region, Uganda]]\n[[Category:Justices of the Supreme Court of Uganda]]\n\n\n{{Uganda-law-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: , \u2192 ,  (3), \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stella_Arach-Amoko"}
{"title_page": "Vida Akoto-Bamfo", "text_new": "{{short description|Ghanaian judge}}\n{{Infobox judge\n | honorific_prefix = \n | name        = Vida Akoto-Bamfo\n | honorific_suffix = \n | image       = \n | alt         = \n | caption     = \n | office      =  [[Supreme Court Judge]]\n | term_start  =  31 October 2009\n | term_end    =  14 February 2019\n | nominator   =  <!--[[John Atta Mills]] -->\n | appointer   =  [[John Atta Mills]]\n | predecessor =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | successor   =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | pronunciation   = \n | birth_name      = \n | birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1949|02|07|df=y}}\n | birth_place     = \n | death_date      =  <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n | death_place     = \n | death_cause     = \n | resting_place   = \n | resting_place_coordinates = \n | citizenship     = \n | nationality     = {{flagicon|GHA}} [[Ghana|Ghanaian]]\n | party           = \n | otherparty      =  <!--For additional political affiliations-->\n | height          =  <!-- \"X cm\", \"X m\"  or \"X ft Y in\" plus optional reference (conversions are automatic) -->\n | spouse          = \n | partner         =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n | relations       = \n | children        = \n | parents         =  <!-- overrides mother and father parameters -->\n | mother          =  <!-- may be used (optionally with father parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays \"Parent(s)\" as label) -->\n | father          =  <!-- may be used (optionally with mother parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays \"Parent(s)\" as label) -->\n | relatives       = \n | residence       = \n | education       = \n | alma_mater      = [[University of Ghana]]<br>[[Ghana School of Law]]\n | occupation      = [[Judge]]\n | profession      = \n | known_for       = \n | salary          = \n | net_worth       =  <!-- Net worth should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n | cabinet         = \n | committees      = \n | portfolio       = \n | awards          =  <!-- For civilian awards - appears as \"Awards\" if |mawards= is not set -->\n | blank1          = \n | data1           = \n | blank2          = \n | data2           = \n | blank3          = \n | data3           = \n | blank4          = \n | data4           = \n | blank5          = \n | data5           = \n | signature       = \n | signature_alt   = \n | website         = \n<!--Embedded templates / Footnotes-->\n | module          = \n | module2         = \n | module3         = \n | module4         = \n | module5         = \n | footnotes       = \n}}\n\n'''Vida Akoto-Bamfo''' is a retired [[Ghana|Ghanaian]] [[Supreme Court Judge]]. She served on the Supreme Court bench from 2009 to 2019.\n\n==Early life and education==\nAkoto-Bamfo was born on 7 February 1949 Mr. Alfred Kingsley Bannerman-Williams and Madam Grace Darkua Dodoo at [[Pokuase]], in the [[Greater Accra Region]] of [[Ghana]].<ref name=\"AKOTO-BAMFO\">{{cite web |title=Give Same Level of Attention to All Cases - Justice Akoto-Bamfo Entreats the Bench As She Exits |url=http://www.judicial.gov.gh/index.php/component/k2/item/368-give-same-level-of-attention-to-all-cases-justice-akoto-bamfo-entreats-the-bench-as-she-exits |website=judicial.gov.gh |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> She had her early education at Accra Royal School in James Town (British Accra). In 1963, she gained admission to [[Mfantsiman Girls' Secondary School]] where she obtained her 'O' Level certificate.<ref name=\"AKOTO-BAMFO\"/> She later continued at [[Aburi Girls' Senior High School]] from 1967 to 1969.<ref name=\"AKOTO-BAMFO\"/> She studied law at the [[University of Ghana]] Law School between 1972 and 1975. She then proceeded to the Ghana Law School in Accra.<ref name=\"newjudges\">{{cite web |title=New Justices Get Approval |url=https://www.modernghana.com/news/246637/1/new-justices-get-approval.html |website=ModernGhana.com |publisher=Modern Ghana |accessdate=30 November 2019 |date=31 October 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nPrior to joining the bench in 1981, Akoto-Bamfo worked at the Attorney-General's Office as a National Service personnel.<ref name=\"AKOTO-BAMFO\"/> She later joined British Indian Insurance Company in [[Accra]], and the now defunct Zenith Assurance as Manager in charge of claims from 1976 to 1981.<ref name=\"AKOTO-BAMFO\"/> There, she was responsible for settling insurance claims. She became a [[District Magistrate]] in 1981.<ref name=\"AKOTO-BAMFO\"/> As a magistrate, she was first stationed at the New Town Magistrate Court for her first two years.<ref name=\"AKOTO-BAMFO\"/> She was later transferred to Cocoa Affairs where she worked as one of the first Magistrates there.<ref name=\"AKOTO-BAMFO\"/> She was later appointed a Circuit Court judge stationed at Tema for a brief while before returning to Cocoa Affairs in 1986.<ref name=\"AKOTO-BAMFO\"/> She remained at Cocoa Affairs from then until 1991 when she was promoted to the [[High Court]] bench.<ref name=\"ghanaweb\">{{cite web |title=Justice Akoto-Bamfo delivers farewell judgment as she retires |url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/Justice-Akoto-Bamfo-delivers-farewell-judgment-as-she-retires-723251 |website=GhanaWeb.com |publisher=GhanaWeb |accessdate=30 November 2019 |date=14 February 2019}}</ref> After serving as a justice of the High Court for three years, she was transferred to [[the Gambia]] on secondment for two years as Chairperson of the Assets Commission.<ref name=\"AKOTO-BAMFO\"/> She was appointed an [[Appeal Court|Appeal Court Judge]] in 1999 and she continued in this position until her nomination and appointment as justice of the [[Supreme Court of Ghana]] by [[John Atta Mills|John Evans Atta Mills]], [[President of Ghana]] in 2009.<ref name=\"newjudges\"/> She retired in February 2019.<ref name=\"ghanaweb\"/> She was appointed together with [[Nasiru Sulemana Gbadegbe]] and [[Benjamin Teiko Aryeetey]] (now retired).<ref name=\"AKOTO-BAMFO\"/> She joined Justices [[Stephen Alan Brobbey]], [[Georgina Theodora Wood]] (then Chief Justice) and [[Samuel Date-Bah|Samuel K. Date-Bah]], who are all retired.<ref name=\"AKOTO-BAMFO\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nVida Akoto-Bamfo was married to the late Eugene Akoto-Bamfo Snr., a Legal Officer.<ref name=\"AKOTO-BAMFO\"/> She identified as a Methodist but fellowships at the Police Church.<ref name=\"AKOTO-BAMFO\"/>\u00a0\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of judges of the Supreme Court of Ghana]]\n*[[Judiciary of Ghana]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Akoto-Bamfo, Vida}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Justices of the Supreme Court of Ghana]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian women judges]]\n\n{{Ghana-bio-stub}}\n{{Africa-law-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ghanaian judge}}\n{{Infobox judge\n | honorific_prefix = \n | name        = Vida Akoto-Bamfo\n | honorific_suffix = \n | image       = \n | alt         = \n | caption     = \n | office      =  [[Supreme Court Judge]]\n | term_start  =  31 October 2009\n | term_end    =  14 February 2019\n | nominator   =  <!--[[John Atta Mills]] -->\n | appointer   =  [[John Atta Mills]]\n | predecessor =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | successor   =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | pronunciation   = \n | birth_name      = \n | birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1949|02|07|df=y}}\n | birth_place     = \n | death_date      =  <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n | death_place     = \n | death_cause     = \n | resting_place   = \n | resting_place_coordinates = \n | citizenship     = \n | nationality     = {{flagicon|GHA}} [[Ghana|Ghanaian]]\n | party           = \n | otherparty      =  <!--For additional political affiliations-->\n | height          =  <!-- \"X cm\