o All Cases - Justice Akoto-Bamfo Entreats the Bench As She Exits |url=http://www.judicial.gov.gh/index.php/component/k2/item/368-give-same-level-of-attention-to-all-cases-justice-akoto-bamfo-entreats-the-bench-as-she-exits |website=judicial.gov.gh |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> She had her early education at Accra Royal School in James Town (British Accra). In 1963, she gained admission to [[Mfantsiman Girls' Secondary School]] where she obtained her 'O' Level certificate.<ref name=\"AKOTO-BAMFO\"/> She later continued at [[Aburi Girls' Senior High School]] from 1967 to 1969.<ref name=\"AKOTO-BAMFO\"/> She studied law at the [[University of Ghana]] Law School between 1972 and 1975. She then proceeded to the Ghana Law School in Accra.<ref name=\"newjudges\">{{cite web |title=New Justices Get Approval |url=https://www.modernghana.com/news/246637/1/new-justices-get-approval.html |website=ModernGhana.com |publisher=Modern Ghana |accessdate=30 November 2019 |date=31 October 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nPrior to joining the bench in 1981, Akoto-Bamfo worked at the Attorney-General\u2019s Office as a National Service personnel.<ref name=\"AKOTO-BAMFO\"/> She later joined British Indian Insurance Company in [[Accra]], and the now defunct Zenith Assurance as Manager in charge of claims from 1976 to 1981.<ref name=\"AKOTO-BAMFO\"/> There, she was responsible for settling insurance claims. She became a [[District Magistrate]] in 1981.<ref name=\"AKOTO-BAMFO\"/> As a magistrate, she was first stationed at the New Town Magistrate Court for her first two years.<ref name=\"AKOTO-BAMFO\"/> She was later transferred to Cocoa Affairs where she worked as one of the first Magistrates there.<ref name=\"AKOTO-BAMFO\"/> She was later appointed a Circuit Court judge stationed at Tema for a brief while before returning to Cocoa Affairs in 1986.<ref name=\"AKOTO-BAMFO\"/> She remained at Cocoa Affairs from then until 1991 when she was promoted to the [[High Court]] bench.<ref name=\"ghanaweb\">{{cite web |title=Justice Akoto-Bamfo delivers farewell judgment as she retires |url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/Justice-Akoto-Bamfo-delivers-farewell-judgment-as-she-retires-723251 |website=GhanaWeb.com |publisher=GhanaWeb |accessdate=30 November 2019 |date=14 February 2019}}</ref> After serving as a justice of the High Court for three years, she was transferred to [[the Gambia]] on secondment for two years as Chairperson of the Assets Commission.<ref name=\"AKOTO-BAMFO\"/> She was appointed an [[Appeal Court|Appeal Court Judge]] in 1999 and she continued in this position until her nomination and appointment as justice of the [[Supreme Court of Ghana]] by [[John Atta Mills|John Evans Atta Mills]], [[President of Ghana]] in 2009.<ref name=\"newjudges\"/> She retired in February 2019.<ref name=\"ghanaweb\"/> She was appointed together with [[Nasiru Sulemana Gbadegbe]] and [[Benjamin Teiko Aryeetey]] (now retired).<ref name=\"AKOTO-BAMFO\"/> She joined Justices [[Stephen Alan Brobbey]], [[Georgina Theodora Wood]] (then Chief Justice) and [[Samuel Date-Bah|Samuel K. Date-Bah]], who are all retired.<ref name=\"AKOTO-BAMFO\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nVida Akoto-Bamfo was married to the late Eugene Akoto-Bamfo Snr., a Legal Officer.<ref name=\"AKOTO-BAMFO\"/> She identified as a Methodist but fellowships at the Police Church.<ref name=\"AKOTO-BAMFO\"/>\u00a0\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of judges of the Supreme Court of Ghana]]\n*[[Judiciary of Ghana]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Akoto-Bamfo, Vida}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Justices of the Supreme Court of Ghana]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian women judges]]\n\n{{Ghana-bio-stub}}\n{{Africa-law-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vida_Akoto-Bamfo"}
{"title_page": "Bola Ajibola", "text_new": "{{Infobox Judge\n|honorific-prefix  = [[Oba (ruler)|Omoba]]\n|name              = Bola Ajibola\n|honorific-suffix  =  [[Order of the British Empire|KBE]]\n|image             = \n|imagesize         = \n|caption           = \n|office            = Minister of Justice of Nigeria\n|term_start        = September 12, 1985\n|term_end          =  December 4, 1991\n|monarch           = \n|predecessor       = \n|successor         = [[Clement Akpamgbo]]\n|office2           = Judge of the International Court of Justice\n|term_start2       = 1991\n|term_end2         = 1994\n|predecessor2 = [[Taslim Olawale Elias|Taslim Elias]]\n|successor2   = [[Abdul Koroma]]\n|birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|1934|03|22}}\n|birth_place       = \n|death_date        = \n|death_place       = \n|restingplace      = \n|birthname         = \n|nationality       = \n|spouse            = \n|residence         = \n|alma_mater        = [[University of London]]\n|occupation        = \n|profession        = \n|religion          = [[Islam]]\n|signature         = \n|website           = \n|footnotes         = \n}}\n'''Bolasodun Adesumbo \"Bola\" Ajibola''', [[Order of the British Empire|KBE]] (born March 22, 1934)<ref name=\"Mielle\">Mielle K. Bulterman, Martin Kuijer [https://books.google.com/books?id=-w25XCGD8bIC&pg=PA145&dq=bola+ajibola&lr=&cd=22#v=onepage&q=bola%20ajibola&f=false Compliance with judgments of international courts]</ref> was an [[Nigerian Federal Ministry of Justice|Attorney General and the Minister of Justice]] of Nigeria from 1985 to 1991 and a Judge of the [[International Court of Justice]] from 1991 to 1994.<ref name=\"ICJ\">{{cite web|url=http://www.icj-cij.org/presscom/files/3/10243.pdf|title=Election of a Member of the International Court of Justice|publisher=ICJ|accessdate=2010-08-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120429004650/http://www.icj-cij.org/presscom/files/3/10243.pdf|archive-date=2012-04-29|url-status=dead}}</ref> He was president of the [[Nigerian Bar Association]] from 1984\u201385.  He was also one of five commissioners on the [[Eritrean-Ethiopian War#Arbitration through the Permanent Court of Arbitration|Eritrea-Ethiopia Boundary Commission]], organized through the [[Permanent Court of Arbitration]].\n\nBorn on March 22, 1934 in [[Owu kingdom|Owu]], near [[Abeokuta]], Nigeria, to the Owu royal family<ref>{{cite book | url =https://books.google.com/books?id=UT7KlSknWDoC&pg=PA238&dq=|title = Common Word: Muslims and Christians on Loving God and Neighbor|author1=Miroslav Volf|author2=Ghazi bin Muhammad (Prince of Jordan.)|author3=Mellisa Yarrington|publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing|year=2010|page=238|isbn =9780802863805}}</ref> of Oba Abdul-Salam Ajibola Gbadela II, who was the traditional ruler of Owu between 1949 and 1972, Ajibola attended Owu Baptist Day School and [[Baptist Boys\u2019 High School]] both in Abeokuta between 1942 and 1955. He obtained his bachelor's degree in Law (LL.B) at the Holborn College of Law, University of London between 1959 and 1962 and was called to the English Bar at the [[Lincoln\u2019s Inn]] in 1962.  He returned to Nigeria to practise the Law, specialising in [[Commercial Law]] and [[International Arbitration]].\n\nHe was the chairman of the panel set up by the [[Plateau State]] government to probe the [[2008 Jos riots]].<ref>[http://allafrica.com/stories/200904300439.html Jos Riots - Politricking With Fire]</ref><ref>[http://www.thetimesofnigeria.com/Article.aspx?id=1342 Plateau Gov Inaugurates Panel To Investigate Jos Riots]</ref> He established crescent university in 2005 in Nigeria which is an Islamic and co-educational institution.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Nigerian Ministers of Justice}}\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20101220125953/http://thenationonlineng.net/web2/articles/225/1/Bola-Ajibola-An-icon-at-75/Page1.html\n*[https://www.google.com/#hl=en&source=hp&q=bola+ajibola&aq=1&aqi=g7g-m1&aql=&oq=bola+aj&gs_rfai=&fp=d3f7de83610b0c52 GoogleSearch]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ajibola, Bola}}\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:Justice ministers of Nigeria]]\n[[Category:International Court of Justice judges]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Nigeria]]\n[[Category:People from Ogun State]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University of London Worldwide]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:20th-century Nigerian lawyers]]\n[[Category:Yoruba legal professionals]]\n[[Category:Yoruba royalty]]\n[[Category:Attorneys General of Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Nigerian judges of United Nations courts and tribunals]]\n\n\n{{Nigeria-law-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Judge\n|honorific-prefix  = [[Oba (ruler)|Omoba]]\n|name              = Bola Ajibola\n|honorific-suffix  =  [[Order of the British Empire|KBE]]\n|image             = \n|imagesize         = \n|caption           = \n|office            = Minister of Justice of Nigeria\n|term_start        = September 12, 1985\n|term_end          =  December 4, 1991\n|monarch           = \n|predecessor       = \n|successor         = [[Clement Akpamgbo]]\n|office2           = Judge of the International Court of Justice\n|term_start2       = 1991\n|term_end2         = 1994\n|predecessor2 = [[Taslim Olawale Elias|Taslim Elias]]\n|successor2   = [[Abdul Koroma]]\n|birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|1934|03|22}}\n|birth_place       = \n|death_date        = \n|death_place       = \n|restingplace      = \n|birthname         = \n|nationality       = \n|spouse            = \n|residence         = \n|alma_mater        = [[University of London]]\n|occupation        = \n|profession        = \n|religion          = [[Islam]]\n|signature         = \n|website           = \n|footnotes         = \n}}\n'''Bolasodun Adesumbo \"Bola\" Ajibola''', [[Order of the British Empire|KBE]] (born March 22, 1934)<ref name=\"Mielle\">Mielle K. Bulterman, Martin Kuijer [https://books.google.com/books?id=-w25XCGD8bIC&pg=PA145&dq=bola+ajibola&lr=&cd=22#v=onepage&q=bola%20ajibola&f=false Compliance with judgments of international courts]</ref> was an [[Nigerian Federal Ministry of Justice|Attorney General and the Minister of Justice]] of Nigeria from 1985 to 1991 and a Judge of the [[International Court of Justice]] from 1991 to 1994.<ref name=\"ICJ\">{{cite web|url=http://www.icj-cij.org/presscom/files/3/10243.pdf|title=Election of a Member of the International Court of Justice|publisher=ICJ|accessdate=2010-08-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120429004650/http://www.icj-cij.org/presscom/files/3/10243.pdf|archive-date=2012-04-29|url-status=dead}}</ref> He was president of the [[Nigerian Bar Association]] from 1984-85.  He was also one of five commissioners on the [[Eritrean-Ethiopian War#Arbitration through the Permanent Court of Arbitration|Eritrea-Ethiopia Boundary Commission]], organized through the [[Permanent Court of Arbitration]].\n\nBorn on March 22, 1934 in [[Owu kingdom|Owu]], near [[Abeokuta]], Nigeria, to the Owu royal family<ref>{{cite book | url =https://books.google.com/books?id=UT7KlSknWDoC&pg=PA238&dq=|title = Common Word: Muslims and Christians on Loving God and Neighbor|author1=Miroslav Volf|author2=Ghazi bin Muhammad (Prince of Jordan.)|author3=Mellisa Yarrington|publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing|year=2010|page=238|isbn =9780802863805}}</ref> of Oba Abdul-Salam Ajibola Gbadela II, who was the traditional ruler of Owu between 1949 and 1972, Ajibola attended Owu Baptist Day School and [[Baptist Boys\u2019 High School]] both in Abeokuta between 1942 and 1955. He obtained his bachelor's degree in Law (LL.B) at the Holborn College of Law, University of London between 1959 and 1962 and was called to the English Bar at the [[Lincoln\u2019s Inn]] in 1962.  He returned to Nigeria to practise the Law, specialising in [[Commercial Law]] and [[International Arbitration]].\n\nHe was the chairman of the panel set up by the [[Plateau State]] government to probe the [[2008 Jos riots]].<ref>[http://allafrica.com/stories/200904300439.html Jos Riots - Politricking With Fire]</ref><ref>[http://www.thetimesofnigeria.com/Article.aspx?id=1342 Plateau Gov Inaugurates Panel To Investigate Jos Riots]</ref> He established crescent university in 2005 in Nigeria which is an Islamic and co-educational institution.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Nigerian Ministers of Justice}}\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20101220125953/http://thenationonlineng.net/web2/articles/225/1/Bola-Ajibola-An-icon-at-75/Page1.html\n*[https://www.google.com/#hl=en&source=hp&q=bola+ajibola&aq=1&aqi=g7g-m1&aql=&oq=bola+aj&gs_rfai=&fp=d3f7de83610b0c52 GoogleSearch]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ajibola, Bola}}\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:Justice ministers of Nigeria]]\n[[Category:International Court of Justice judges]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Nigeria]]\n[[Category:People from Ogun State]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University of London Worldwide]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:20th-century Nigerian lawyers]]\n[[Category:Yoruba legal professionals]]\n[[Category:Yoruba royalty]]\n[[Category:Attorneys General of Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Nigerian judges of United Nations courts and tribunals]]\n\n\n{{Nigeria-law-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1984-85 \u2192 1984\u201385", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bola_Ajibola"}
{"title_page": "Umm al-Darda", "text_new": "'''Umm al-Darda al-Kubra''' ([[Arabic]]: \u0623\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0631\u062f\u0627\u0621 \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0628\u0631\u0649) was a companion of prophet [[Muhammad]]. She was a prominent jurist during the 7th century in Damascus.<ref>Suleman, Mehrunisha; Rajbee, Afaaf. \"The Lost Female Scholars of Islam\". Emel magazine. Emel magazine</ref> She lectured in the male section of the mosque. As an orphan child, under the sponsorship of Abu Darda, she prayed with men, until she reached maturity at which point she started praying with women. She became a teacher of [[hadith]] and [[fiqh]] and lectured in the men's section. Her husband was the fellow companion [[Abu Darda]].\n\nOne of her students, [[Abd al-Malik ibn Marwan|'''\u02bf'''Abd al-Malik ibn Marw\u0101n]], was the 5th [[Umayyad Caliphate|Umayyad]] caliph.<ref>Carla Power, \"A Secret History\", New York Times Magazine, 25 February 2007.</ref><ref>Ato Quayson, Girish Daswani, A Companion to Diaspora and Transnationalism, Chapter 29. {{ISBN|1118320646}}.</ref> He studied [[fiqh]] under Umm al-Darda<ref>Suleman, Mehrunisha; Rajbee, Afaaf. \"The Lost Female Scholars of Islam\". Emel magazine. Emel magazine.</ref><ref>Nadwi, M. A. (2007). Al-Muhaddithat: The Women Scholars in Islam. Interface Publications. {{ISBN|9780955454516}} {{pn|date=June 2017}}</ref> The 14th-century Muslim historian [[Ibn Khaldun]] states, \"'''\u02bf'''Abd al-Malik ibn Marwan is one of the greatest Arab and Muslim Caliphs. He followed in the footsteps of [[Umar|'''\u02bf'''Umar ibn al-Khattab]], the Commander of the Believers, in regulating state affairs.\" <ref>Montefiore, Simon Sebag (2012-05-17). Titans of the Middle East. Quercus Publishing. {{ISBN|9781743511237}}.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Hafsa bint Sirin]]\n*[[Umm al-Darda as-Sughra]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Female Sahabah]]\n[[Category:People from Damascus]]\n[[Category:Syrian Muslims]]\n[[Category:Syrian women]]\n\n{{law-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Umm al-Darda al-Kubra''' ([[Arabic]]: \u0623\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0631\u062f\u0627\u0621 \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0628\u0631\u0649) was a companion of prophet [[Muhammad]]. She was a prominent jurist during the 7th century in Damascus.<ref>Suleman, Mehrunisha; Rajbee, Afaaf. \"The Lost Female Scholars of Islam\". Emel magazine. Emel magazine</ref> She lectured in the male section of the mosque. As an orphan child, under the sponsorship of Abu Darda, she prayed with men, until she reached maturity at which point she started praying with women. She became a teacher of [[hadith]] and [[fiqh]] and lectured in the men\u2019s section. Her husband was the fellow companion [[Abu Darda]].\n\nOne of her students, [[Abd al-Malik ibn Marwan|'''\u02bf'''Abd al-Malik ibn Marw\u0101n]], was the 5th [[Umayyad Caliphate|Umayyad]] caliph.<ref>Carla Power, \"A Secret History\", New York Times Magazine, 25 February 2007.</ref><ref>Ato Quayson, Girish Daswani, A Companion to Diaspora and Transnationalism, Chapter 29. {{ISBN|1118320646}}.</ref> He studied [[fiqh]] under Umm al-Darda<ref>Suleman, Mehrunisha; Rajbee, Afaaf. \"The Lost Female Scholars of Islam\". Emel magazine. Emel magazine.</ref><ref>Nadwi, M. A. (2007). Al-Muhaddithat: The Women Scholars in Islam. Interface Publications. {{ISBN|9780955454516}} {{pn|date=June 2017}}</ref> The 14th-century Muslim historian [[Ibn Khaldun]] states, \"'''\u02bf'''Abd al-Malik ibn Marwan is one of the greatest Arab and Muslim Caliphs. He followed in the footsteps of [[Umar|'''\u02bf'''Umar ibn al-Khattab]], the Commander of the Believers, in regulating state affairs.\" <ref>Montefiore, Simon Sebag (2012-05-17). Titans of the Middle East. Quercus Publishing. {{ISBN|9781743511237}}.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Hafsa bint Sirin]]\n*[[Umm al-Darda as-Sughra]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Female Sahabah]]\n[[Category:People from Damascus]]\n[[Category:Syrian Muslims]]\n[[Category:Syrian women]